subSection.paragraph:
With approximately 4750 species grouped in 26 families, parasitic plants account for 1,6% of all angiosperms (
Nickrent, 2020
). Parasitic plants are components of almost all terrestrial vegetation 
types
(
Heide-Jørgensen, 2008
). In plants, the parasitic lifestyle is characterized by developing an intrusive organ called a haustorium, a vascular bridge that connects the two plants that also acts on attachment and host tissue penetration (
Joel, 2013
) and absorbs water and nutrients from host-plant vascular tissue. Holoparasites (no photosynthesis and chlorophyll absent) have lower transpiration rates than hemiparasites (photoautotrophic and chlorophyll present) because holoparasites are underground for most of their lifecycle; even after emergence, they do not photosynthesize due to the lack of leaves necessary for effective transpiration (
Heide-Jørgensen, 2008
; 
Westwood, 2013
). Holoparasites infect both the phloem and xylem of the host tissue and rely on the host to supply both organic and inorganic nutrients (
Hibberd et al., 1999
). Haustorium cells metabolize host-derived nutrients, creating a parasite-specific metabolic profile (
Abbes et al., 2009
; 
Draie et al., 2011
; P´eron et al., 2016), which may be completely different in holoparasites

Parasitism represents the most extreme interaction between plants, and plant parasitism offers a unique opportunity to study correlational nutritional relationships (
Yoder, 2001
). Interestingly, parasites generally accumulate more inorganic and organic compounds than their hosts, which has a notable effect on subsequent processes and associated mechanisms (
Hibberd et al., 1999
; 
Abbes et al., 2009
; 
Llugany et al., 2009
). Therefore, holoparasites lower their water potentials by accumulating high levels of osmotically active compounds such as mineral ions, sugars, and sugar alcohols (
Westwood, 2013
). The gradient of the water potential between the host and the parasite is a driving force for water flow (
Ehleringer and Marshall, 1995
). However, many questions remain about this process, especially regarding which 
types
of materials are translocated from host to parasite, whether the parasite is selective in extracting certain compounds and excluding others, and how the parasite uses the acquired material, including toxic compounds (
Westwood, 2013
). An interesting and poorly understood phenomenon is the relation between the parasitic lifestyle in plants and resistance against toxic trace elements in polluted soils. Parasites can reduce the concentration of heavy metals in the host due to their high accumulation tendencies. However, identifying the mechanism by which this occurs and determining whether compounds withdrawn from the host are already chelated to reduce toxicity prior to parasite uptake, whether the parasite has specific chelating mechanisms, or whether parasitic plants may play a role in bioremediation in removing metals, salt, or other soil contaminants are still required (
Llugany et al., 2009
; 
Watson, 2009
; 
Bani et al., 2018
; 
Turnau et al., 2018
; 
Dimitrakopoulos et al., 2021
).

Parasites can be considered keystone species because they influence the individual growth, reproduction, and allometry of other species, as well as ecosystems and ecological communities through their effects on trophic interactions in abiotic compounds and other organisms (
Press and Phoenix, 2005
). It is also interesting that hyperparasitic interactions between parasitic plants may affect not only the ecology of individual species or nutrient sharing but also modulate their ecosystem impacts (
Krasylenko et al., 2021
). Some parasites are allogenic engineers that change the environment by transforming materials from one physical state to another, particularly in nutrient-poor communities, from less available forms into more labile forms (
Press and Phoenix, 2005
). Parasitic plants also tend to have much higher nutrient concentrations than their hosts (
Pate, 1995
), usually several times the N and P in the leaves of root hemiparasites (
Quested et al., 2002
, 
2003a
, 
2003b
; 
Ameloot et al., 2008
). Thus, they have considerable impacts on local biogeochemical cycling due to their enriched and easily decomposed litter (
Ameloot et al., 2008
). If we look at parasitic plants not only through the prism of dependence and parasite–host interaction, we can easily see moderators of the entire ecosystem in them, particularly by enriching the environment with minerals. 
Watson (2009)
proposed, Dryads, rather than Robin Hood or Dracula, as a mythological analogy consistent with the role of a parasite in facilitating the growth of nearby plants.

Soils with high heavy metal contents provide very restrictive habitats for plants due to phytotoxicity, resulting in severe selection pressures and the rise of genetically altered ecotypes with specific tolerances to heavy metals that adapt through microevolutionary processes (
Baker et al., 2010
). Parasites, particularly obligate parasites, could provide a better understanding of the biological availability of pollutants in ecosystems. The accumulation of heavy metals in the indicator parts of 

O. laxissima

was higher than that tolerated in most plants, which indicates that it is resistant to the negative effects associated with these elements. It is also worth emphasizing that the holoparasite we investigated, similar to most parasites in relation to the size of the hosts, has a much lower biomass than its tree hosts, thus not having a large area across which these metals could be distributed or diluted. It can be assumed that the uptake of excessive amounts of heavy metals from the host may function as a protective effect for the host. Parasites can also modify the host’ s physiological or biochemical response to contamination in different directions, as both stressors can act synergistically (parasite plus contaminants) or antagonistically. Interestingly, animal parasites have been reported to be pollutant sinks, such as tapeworm-infected fish that exhibited lower heavy metal contents than noninfected fish (
Sures et al., 2017
). This raises the question of whether parasites alter the dynamics of contaminants in the trophic cycle and how this affects the health and interaction of organisms; as another example, the Cd content may be several thousand times higher in tapeworms and nematodes than in the tissues of their host (
Sures et al., 2017
). Holoparasites are nonphotosynthetic and, therefore, less sensitive to heavy metals. High heavy metal concentrations in the soil can be toxic to the host. However, the strong uptake by the parasite, as indicated by the high accumulation factor, reduces its concentration in the host plant, thus reducing its negative impact on physiology.

The uptake of large amounts of heavy metals by 

Orobanche

can serve several functions. Heavy metals can help the host function in a contaminated environment. Uptake by the parasite reduces the concentration of heavy metals in the plant. Such a relationship was also found in the examined 

O. laxissima

. In addition, 
Turnau et al. (2018)
pointed to the reallocation of toxic metals from the host tissue to the parasite stem. This suggests that the parasite may play an important role in lowering the concentration of metals. Heavy metals can also play an important role in the development of the parasite. Their accumulation capacity can give them an advantage over others and affect other species and ecosystems, such as by elemental allelopathy (e.g., for some microbes and pathogens). They can increase drought resistance, influence neighbours (interference/allelopathy), or provide defence against natural enemies (
Boyd and Martens, 1998
; 
Pollard et al., 2002
; 
Rascio and Navari-Izzo, 2011
). It is possible that high quantities of heavy metals (or metabolites) are toxic or unsavoury to animals and pathogens (
Rascio and Navari-Izzo, 2011
). It has also been noted that animals only eat parts of hyperaccumulating plants that contain the least amount of heavy metals, such as seeds (
Boyd, 2007
). The first author’ s long-term observations show that the holoparasitic 
Orobanchaceae
are very resistant to insect pests or fungal diseases, and they are usually not eaten by herbivores. Apart from the ability to accumulate and tolerate metals (not every habitat is their source), resistance to insects and pathogens is probably more influenced by metabolites characteristic of these holoparasites, namely, polyphenols (specifically phenylethanoid glycosides; see Subsection 3.2). It was found that the biosynthesis of polyphenols, such as flavonoids, is strongly enhanced in plants owing to excessive metal content. Organic acids and amino acids also play an important role in metal tolerance (
Corso, 2020
). Some species that grow next to metal-accumulating plants may benefit from this neighbourhood, that is, protection against pathogens and herbivores, including the soil around these plants, and the mulch formed from parasites is much richer in metals (
Mehdawi et al., 2011
). It has been shown that trees absorb Ni from deep soil layers and accumulate it in leaves, which then increases Ni levels in the upper soil layers as the leaves fall (
Sagner et al., 1998
). High soil concentrations can inhibit the sprouting and growth of other competing plants (Mehdavi et al., 2011), creating favourable conditions for organisms to tolerate metals (
Mehdawi and Pilon-Smits, 2012
). Heavy metals can be chelated in the cytosol and compartmentalized, for example, in vacuoles, apoplastic space, or epidermal trichomes (
Lambers et al., 2008
). Trichomes are found densely on flowers or stems with scales in most holoparasitic 
Orobanchaceae
, but their role in accumulating or removing metals requires further research.

Moreover, the results showed that the higher the amount of polyphenols in the parasite was, the higher the antiradical activity, reducing activity, and high the ability to inhibit the activity of α- amylase and α- glucosidase (
Table 5
). Many authors have confirmed such dependencies (
Podsedek et al., 2014
; 
Kruczek et al., 2020
). However, a higher scavenging ability of reactive oxygen species can be observed when they are complexed with metals than with polyphenols alone, particularly flavonols (
Corso et al., 2020
). In addition, the results showed that more polyphenols in the parasite and host affected the high accumulation of Cu and Zn and lowered the accumulation of Fe. However, further research investigation is required to validate this relationship. This result may be due to the ability of the flavonol pathway to accumulate metals and create complexes with polyphenols. Organic acids and amino acids, which play a role in metal tolerance and hyperaccumulation, have recently been suggested for flavonoids. Flavonoids are phenolic compounds characterized by two benzene rings linked by a heterocyclic pyran ring and are primarily found in plants as 
O
-glycosides. Flavonoid biosynthesis is strongly enhanced in plants by excess metal (
Corso et al., 2020
). In turn, the stability of metal-polyphenol complexes depends on pH, and several polyphenols exhibit a higher metal-binding ability at pH 7 (cytosolic pH) than at pH 5.5 (vacuolar pH) (
Catapano et al., 2017
). Depending on the pH, flavonoids may play a significant role in chelating metals in various cell organelles (
Corso et al., 2020
). According to Kova´ˇcik et al. (2008), polyphenolic metabolism is a complex compendium that shows constant dynamics of action. This process provides constant protection of plant tissues against oxidative stress induced by excess metals (Kova´ˇcik et al., 2008).

inflammatory, and wound healing potential (
Moulaoui et al., 2015
; 
Caudullo and Houston Durrant, 2016
), and it is known to occur in forests, on slopes, and in ravines, on cinnamonic and brown forest soils in 
Georgia
(
Lachashvili et al., 2017
).
